      <hedline>
        <hl1>Edinburgh</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David F Musto letter notes that Marilyn Stasio's Jan 12 comment on Edinburgh crime writers omitted Sherlock Holmes; adds that many of his adventures are sited in Scottish city, disguised as London; Stasio comments (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: It was criminal for Marilyn Stasio, in her essay on Edinburgh crime writers, ''A Wonderful Place for a Murder'' (Jan. 12) to omit the names of Arthur Conan Doyle and Sherlock Holmes. Doyle was born in Edinburgh and completed medical school there. The Edinburgh University historian Owen Dudley Edwards has pointed out that the origin and sites of many Holmesian adventures are in Edinburgh although they were described as London settings, doubtless to appease The Strand Magazine's editor.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: It was criminal for Marilyn Stasio, in her essay on Edinburgh crime writers, ''A Wonderful Place for a Murder'' (Jan. 12) to omit the names of Arthur Conan Doyle and Sherlock Holmes. Doyle was born in Edinburgh and completed medical school there. The Edinburgh University historian Owen Dudley Edwards has pointed out that the origin and sites of many Holmesian adventures are in Edinburgh although they were described as London settings, doubtless to appease The Strand Magazine's editor.</p>
        <p>If, however, Ms. Stasio pleads in her defense that Holmes is not a fictional detective she is pardoned.</p>
        <p>DAVID F. MUSTO</p>
        <p>New Haven</p>
        <p>Ms. Stasio responds: I am aware, of course, of Edinburgh's No. 1 citizen. But in our hearts and minds, his master creation will forever and always abide at 221B Baker Street.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
